    <title>The White House started posting on Reddit to talk about Hurricane Milton</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="reddit account page for user whitehouse" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/f51hwCpmKAq9ojIe-qCbo6TR9ts=/0x0:2263x1509/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73640883/Screenshot_2024_10_08_at_5.09.48_PM.0.jpeg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;The earliest post on the account is a picture of Biden getting briefed on the hurricanes.&lt;/em&gt; | Screenshot: The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="pMyqbZ"&gt;Reddit isn’t the first place you’d think to see official statements and news coming from the federal government, but today, The White House is on the site making posts. You’ll often see staffers posting on social media platforms like Instagram and X to announce updates and reach a larger audience, so this feels new. The Biden administration’s “whitehouse” account &lt;a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/whitehouse/"&gt;has new posts&lt;/a&gt; in subreddits r/NorthCarolina and r/Georgia to discuss the federal response to Hurricane Helene and Hurricane Milton.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="5dAW2k"&gt;“Yep, it’s really us!” the White House account says in one of the threads. Usually, that’s not an entirely convincing way to prove your identity, but Reddit’s Gina Antonini tells &lt;em&gt;The Verge&lt;/em&gt; in an email that it is indeed a legitimate account. Antonini...&lt;/p&gt;
